Parliament, Sunday 01 November 2020 – Questions to the Deputy President and Clusters, a debate on a matter of national importance and consideration of committee reports including 51 committee meetings are some of the issues on the Parliament programme this week.
	
	The Deputy President will be in the National Council of Provinces (NCOP) on Wednesday to respond to Questions for Oral Reply. These Questions are one of the mechanisms Parliament uses to hold the Executive to account. During the same sitting, the House will consider the Select Committee on Finance’s report on the Revised Fiscal Framework.
	
	During its plenary on Tuesday, the National Assembly (NA) will debate a matter of national importance looking at “the impact of economic lives of the most vulnerable and poor of commuters due to ongoing damage to public rail infrastructure.” The plenary will also consider committee reports amongst them a report of the Portfolio Committee on Women, Youth and Persons with Disabilities on the Draft Notice on Determination of salaries and allowances of commissioners of Commission for Gender Equality.
	
	The NA’s plenary on Wednesday will consider Questions for Oral Reply from Ministers in Cluster 4 (Economics).
	
	On Thursday, the NA will hold two virtual mini-plenaries to discuss matters of national importance sponsored by the Democratic Alliance and the Economic Freedom Fighters. The NCOP will hold Questions to Cluster 2A Social Services with Ministers of Health and Sports, Arts and Culture. The two Houses, the NA and the NCOP, will hold their programming committee meetings to discuss their business.
	
	On Friday, the Parliamentary Group on International Relations (PGIR) will hold a workshop and the Women’s Charter Review Law Reform Conference.
	
	About 51 meetings of Committees from both the NA and the NCOP are scheduled for this week. The business of Committees this week includes public hearings on the 2020 Medium Term Budget Policy Statement of the Standing Committee on Finance and the Select Committee of Finance.
	
